<span>6.6&nbsp;</span><h4 id=apply-for-licenses-and-permits>Apply for licenses and permits.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-apply-for-license-and-permits-288x288-20200729_2023-09-24-135809_msod.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Apply for licenses and permits."></div></div><p>To start a cleaning business you need a regular business license or a cleaning business license, depending on your state or local government. Search the <a
href="https://www.sba.gov/business-guide/launch-your-business/apply-licenses-permits">Small Business Administration's</a> licenses and permits page to find out if you need a cleaning license to work in your area. From there you need to file necessary applications to become a licensed cleaning business.</p></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-cleaning-business-section7" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>7.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=get-funding>Get funding.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-cleaning-business-section7-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>7.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=calculate-your-startup-costs>Calculate your startup costs.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-determine-your-startup-costs-288x288-20200729.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Calculate your startup costs."></div></div><p>Depending on the scale of your cleaning business, your startup costs can be comparatively low, ensuring debt starts at a minimum. The startup costs linked with starting a cleaning business include the price of cleaning supplies and equipment, marketing, insurance, and business licenses (if applicable). The items you need will depend on your businessâ€™s cleaning services.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-cleaning-business-section7-step2" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>7.2&nbsp;</span><h4 id=apply-for-a-loan-with-the-small-business-administration>Apply for a loan with the Small Business Administration (SBA).</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-apply-for-an-sba-loan-288x288-20200724.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Apply for a loan with the Small Business Administration (SBA)."></div></div><p>These loans are managed by the Small Business Administration, and help businesses with limited financial alternatives through federally-backed lending to access funding at low-interest rates.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-cleaning-business-section7-step3" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>7.3&nbsp;</span><h4 id=get-investors>Get investors.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-get-investors-288x288-20200729.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Get investors."></div></div><p>Network until you find your investors. Approach family and friends who have the capital to invest in your cleaning business. Also, try to get an angel investorâ€”an affluent person who invests in you rather than in the viability of your venture.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-cleaning-business-section7-step4" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>7.4&nbsp;</span><h4 id=explore-small-business-loans>Explore small business loans.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-explore-small-business-loans-288x288-20200729.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Explore small business loans."></div></div><p>Your cleaning business can use a small business loan to purchase equipment, inventory, and more. Small business lending includes microloans, bank loans, credit cards, venture capital, and SBA-backed loans.</p></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-cleaning-business-section8" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>8.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=set-your-hourly-rate>Set your hourly rate.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-cleaning-business-section8-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>8.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=consider-your-cleaning-services-and-expertise>Consider your cleaning services and expertise.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-set-your-hourly-rate-288x288-20200729.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Consider your cleaning services and expertise."></div></div><p>Once you have a set hourly rate, you can start budgeting for transportation, labor, marketing, and specialty cleaning services. When establishing your hourly rate, be sure to include your expertise and previous experience. In addition, your rate should largely depend on the size of the job.</p><p>For example, if you are expected to clean a commercial building, you need to consider the size of the building, the facilities you are expected to clean, and the time you need to finish the entire building. In these cases, opt for charging per square foot.</p></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-cleaning-business-section9" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>9.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=purchase-a-transport-vehicle>Purchase a transport vehicle.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-cleaning-business-section9-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>9.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=try-not-to-overspend-on-a-transport-vehicle>Try not to overspend on a transport vehicle.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-try-not-to-overspend-288x288-20200729.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Try not to overspend on a transport vehicle."></div></div><p>Your cleaning service's success hinges on how fast your workers can reach job sites. You can't rely on public transport or personal transport arrangements made by your staff, as you would need to move heavy equipment in many cases.</p><p>If you are starting a residential cleaning business without a crew, you can use your private motor vehicle until you expand. Bear in mind that some states require you to get a commercial license plate before you are allowed to use your private vehicle for business purposes.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-cleaning-business-section9-step2" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>9.2&nbsp;</span><h4 id=choose-a-vehicle-with-good-storage-space>Choose a vehicle with good storage space.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-look-for-a-vehicle-that-offers-loads-of-storage-288x288-20200729.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Choose a vehicle with good storage space."></div></div><p>The best vehicle for your cleaning business is a van, truck, station wagon, or SUV. Your cleaning business needs a heavy-duty vehicleâ€”and eventually more than oneâ€”to store and transport your staff and equipment. The vehicle you need depends on the type and the size of your equipment.</p><div
